They use pan genome minimizer graph:

Instead of mapping an individual's DNA to a single linear "reference genome",
a pan genome captures the collective genetic diversity of an entire species
or population. It accounts for all the core genes present in every example and
the accessory genome (present in only some individuals).

Minimizers are an effective approach to reduce the data complexity and volume
that needs to be dealt with by genomics methods to efficiently utilize or
simply query information. This is achieved by creating “sketches” of sequences
that occupy less space compared to the sequences themselves.

Massive Scalability: It allows researchers to easily map massive datasets
(e.g., hundreds of thousands of bacterial or human genomes) into a data
structure that takes up just gigabytes instead of terabytes of memory.
Improved Accuracy: By using a graph instead of a single reference genome,
researchers reduce bias, more easily identify complex structural variants
(like large insertions, deletions, or inversions), and improve the speed of
mapping sequencing data.
Tooling: This approach forms the mathematical basis for popular modern
genomics tools like Minigraph-Cactus and minimizer-space de Bruijn graphs.
